# 30_styles_scriptable_smoke — fourth row-bound model Scriptable
# end-to-end (s222 m1 + fix-1), modelled on
# 29_swatches_scriptable_smoke. Second LIBRARY-collection Scriptable;
# layers and guides wrap SceneNode collections, swatches and styles
# wrap project-scoped libraries.
#
# Two addressing surfaces, one router:
#
#   styles           — collection. ONE registry entry. Set verbs (new,
#                      delete, duplicate, rename, category, find_by_name)
#                      and set queries (count, all_ids, user_ids,
#                      app_ids).
#   styles.<id>      — per-instance proxy. NOT in the registry —
#                      materialised on demand, destroyed at end-of-
#                      statement. Element verbs (rename / category)
#                      and element queries (name / category /
#                      is_built_in / iid).
#
# ── Where styles differ from swatches ─────────────────────────────────────
#
# StyleLibrary's vocabulary is "app" (built-in, read-only) and "user"
# (per-project, editable), not "default" and "custom". The Scriptable
# follows the model's terms: `user_ids` / `app_ids` (not custom_ids /
# default_ids), `is_built_in` (not is_default). Tests below assert
# against these names.
#
# Styles also have a `category` field on the proxy — a string the panel
# uses as a section header. The smoke exercises proxy `category` (write)
# and the corresponding read query, plus the collection-level
# `category` verb with the "<id>" "<cat>" two-arg form.
#
# ── fix-1: panel navigation on new/duplicate ──────────────────────────────
#
# After a successful `new` or `duplicate`, the Scriptable navigates
# the StylesPanel's active category to the new style's category. This
# is the styles-side parallel of the s221 swatches fix-1 (which mirrored
# add_to_palette into the SwatchesScriptable so chips became visible).
# Different mechanism — set_active_category writes panel state, not
# library state — but same end-user payoff: the user sees the result
# of the script without having to navigate the dropdown manually.
#
# The smoke asserts this via `pnl_styles active_category` after each
# `new`/`duplicate`. The verb itself returns the new style's id (as
# before); the navigation is a side-effect on the panel.
#
# ── Test isolation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Every style this script creates is bound to a script-local variable
# at creation time. Existing styles (the three app stubs + any user
# styles in the project at script start) are NEVER renamed, deleted,
# re-categorised, or recoloured. The teardown step at the bottom
# deletes only the styles we created, by bound id.
#
# Same iid-binding pattern as the guides and swatches smokes (which
# use bound vars because guides have no name field and swatch names
# aren't guaranteed unique). Style names are also not unique by
# construction; iid-binding is the right choice.
#
# ── Undo coverage ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Every mutating verb pushes a command into the doc's CommandHistory.
# The smoke can't directly assert "the stack grew by one" — there's no
# script verb for undo today (commands ride a separate plane from the
# script-level state). What the smoke DOES verify is the round-trip:
# rename A then rename back, set category then revert, etc. If a verb
# forgot to push a command, the round-trip still passes; manual Ctrl+Z
# after the script finishes is the second half of the test — every
# operation should be individually undoable.
#
# ── Phases ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   1. BUILD UP  — capture baseline counts, create three test styles
#                  in a private category, bind each id to a variable
#                  (a / b / c).
#   2. VALIDATE  — exercise collection queries, app-tier guards via
#                  app:default, proxy verbs (rename / category),
#                  proxy queries, find_by_name on each bound style,
#                  duplicate.
#   3. TEAR DOWN — delete every test style; verify count returns to
#                  baseline.

#[sub] === Phase 1: BUILD UP ===
#[sub] Capture baseline so teardown can verify cleanup. count is an
#[sub] integer, comparable in assert via simple equality. user_ids
#[sub] and app_ids are comma-separated strings — useful to print for
#[sub] visual diff, but NOT comparable via `assert == var` because
#[sub] variable substitution is bare-text (commas in the substituted
#[sub] value would break the line tokeniser; this is the same
#[sub] limitation the swatches smoke documents).

get styles count
set count_before to result
get styles all_ids
get styles app_ids
get styles user_ids

#[sub] Capture panel state before any mutation. The panel's
#[sub] active_category sits wherever the project's view state left it
#[sub] (typically "Built-in" on a fresh project, app-tier). The
#[sub] fix-1 navigation step on `new` and `duplicate` will move this;
#[sub] visual `get` here makes the transition observable in the trace.

get pnl_styles active_category

#[sub] Create three test styles. Each lands in a private category
#[sub] ("smoke_test") so the existing user-tier categories (if any)
#[sub] aren't polluted. `styles new` returns the new id; `set X to
#[sub] result` binds it. Empty name and empty category are both legal
#[sub] (a default style with empty everything is what
#[sub] action_create_empty seeds before the dialog opens) but we pass
#[sub] explicit values so find_by_name and category-round-trip can
#[sub] target our styles.

styles new "smoke_test_a" "smoke_test"
set a to result
assert styles.a name == "smoke_test_a"
assert styles.a category == "smoke_test"
assert styles.a is_built_in == false
#[sub] fix-1: the panel should now be sitting on the user-tier
#[sub] "smoke_test" category. Subsequent `new` calls with the same
#[sub] category are panel no-ops (set_active_category short-circuits
#[sub] when already there).
assert pnl_styles active_category == "smoke_test"

styles new "smoke_test_b" "smoke_test"
set b to result
assert styles.b name == "smoke_test_b"
assert styles.b category == "smoke_test"
assert styles.b is_built_in == false

styles new "smoke_test_c" "smoke_test"
set c to result
assert styles.c name == "smoke_test_c"
assert styles.c category == "smoke_test"
assert styles.c is_built_in == false

#[sub] iid query — round-trips the binding key. A script can `get
#[sub] styles.<var> iid` to verify it has the right handle (same
#[sub] shape as SwatchProxy::iid / LayerProxy::iid / GuideProxy::iid).
#[sub] Returned value equals the bound variable; we don't assert
#[sub] equality directly (no string-comparison-against-variable form
#[sub] yet) but the presence of the value proves the proxy resolved.

get styles.a iid
get styles.b iid
get styles.c iid

#[sub] === Phase 2: VALIDATE ===

#[sub] Collection-level queries. count should be baseline + 3. all_ids,
#[sub] user_ids, app_ids are printed for visual diff. app_ids must be
#[sub] identical to the baseline (the Scriptable can't touch the app
#[sub] tier), and user_ids must contain our three test ids plus
#[sub] whatever was already there.

get styles count
get styles all_ids
get styles user_ids
get styles app_ids

#[sub] find_by_name — collection verb (parameterised query workaround,
#[sub] same shape as SwatchesScriptable::find_by_name). Invoke-shaped
#[sub] today because query() can't take args; the bare form
#[sub] `styles find_by_name "X"` falls through to invoke and the
#[sub] result lands in the result slot for capture. First-hit
#[sub] semantics; our names are unique within the test so each returns
#[sub] the bound id.

styles find_by_name "smoke_test_a"
set found_a to result
styles find_by_name "smoke_test_b"
set found_b to result
styles find_by_name "smoke_test_c"
set found_c to result
# find_by_name miss returns "" — we don't bind it because empty-string
# binds would round-trip as `styles.` (no suffix), which can_resolve
# rejects. Operator can confirm visually that the result slot was
# empty on the last find_by_name call.
styles find_by_name "no_such_style_in_any_tier"
assert styles.found_a name == "smoke_test_a"
assert styles.found_b name == "smoke_test_b"
assert styles.found_c name == "smoke_test_c"

#[sub] App-tier read access — `app:default` is one of the three
#[sub] hardcoded app stubs and is always present. We can't dot-address
#[sub] `styles.app:default` because the colon isn't a valid identifier
#[sub] character (substitute_tokens stops at the colon), but the
#[sub] resolver itself accepts it — listener splits on `.` and the
#[sub] suffix "app:default" reaches find_style verbatim. So the dotted
#[sub] form works; we just can't bind it through a variable.

get styles.app:default name
get styles.app:default category
get styles.app:default is_built_in

#[sub] Proxy rename round-trip on `a`. UpdateStyleCommand carries
#[sub] full before/after snapshots; only header.name differs. Skip-
#[sub] no-op guard: rename to the same name doesn't push a command.

styles.a rename "smoke_test_a_renamed"
assert styles.a name == "smoke_test_a_renamed"
styles.a rename "smoke_test_a"
assert styles.a name == "smoke_test_a"

#[sub] Collection-level rename round-trip on `b`. Same
#[sub] UpdateStyleCommand, just accessed via the collection-with-id
#[sub] form.

styles rename b "smoke_test_b_renamed"
assert styles.b name == "smoke_test_b_renamed"
styles rename b "smoke_test_b"
assert styles.b name == "smoke_test_b"

#[sub] Proxy category round-trip on `c`. UpdateStyleCommand again,
#[sub] this time with only header.category diffed. Empty category is
#[sub] meaningful — it moves the style to the "(uncategorised)"
#[sub] panel bucket. The round-trip restores the test category.

styles.c category "smoke_test_other"
assert styles.c category == "smoke_test_other"
styles.c category ""
assert styles.c category == ""
styles.c category "smoke_test"
assert styles.c category == "smoke_test"

#[sub] Collection-level category set — two-arg "<id>" "<cat>" form.
#[sub] Same UpdateStyleCommand, just accessed by id instead of dotted
#[sub] addressing.

styles category a "smoke_test_other"
assert styles.a category == "smoke_test_other"
styles category a "smoke_test"
assert styles.a category == "smoke_test"

#[sub] Duplicate `a`. New id, fresh entry, " copy" appended to name,
#[sub] category preserved verbatim from the source (so the duplicate
#[sub] also lands in "smoke_test"). is_built_in is false — duplicates
#[sub] always land in the user tier regardless of the source's tier.

styles duplicate a
set a_dup to result
assert styles.a_dup name == "smoke_test_a copy"
assert styles.a_dup category == "smoke_test"
assert styles.a_dup is_built_in == false
#[sub] fix-1: duplicate of a user-tier style with category "smoke_test"
#[sub] leaves the panel on "smoke_test" (no-op switch — already there).
assert pnl_styles active_category == "smoke_test"

#[sub] App-tier guard. Every mutating verb refuses on an app-tier id,
#[sub] returning Null without pushing a command. Exercise each mutating
#[sub] verb against `app:default`; the style is unchanged across the
#[sub] sequence. Direct quoted-string args because we can't bind
#[sub] colon-containing ids to variables. The defaults-tier "duplicate
#[sub] to user tier" affordance IS available — we exercise that too,
#[sub] then immediately delete the result so we don't leave residue.

styles rename "app:default" "would_break_app_tier_if_this_worked"
get styles.app:default name
# Visual check: name still "Default", not the would-break-* string
# above. We don't assert the literal "Default" because that ties the
# test to the StyleLibrary's hardcoded stub name; the get above is the
# evidence.

styles category "app:default" "would_move_app_tier_if_this_worked"
get styles.app:default category
# Visual check: category still "Built-in".

styles delete "app:default"
get styles count
# Visual check: count unchanged from the post-duplicate value above.

#[sub] Duplicate the app stub — this IS allowed, and the duplicate
#[sub] lands in the user tier. " copy" appended; category inherited
#[sub] verbatim ("Built-in" — yes, this leaves a "Built-in" entry in
#[sub] the user-categories list, which is exactly what
#[sub] StylesPanel::action_duplicate does in the panel-driven path
#[sub] too). Delete it immediately to avoid leaving residue in the
#[sub] user-tier "Built-in" category.

styles duplicate "app:default"
set app_dup to result
assert styles.app_dup name == "Default copy"
assert styles.app_dup is_built_in == false
#[sub] fix-1: duplicate of an app-tier style inherits its category
#[sub] verbatim ("Built-in"), but the new style lands in the user
#[sub] tier — so the panel switches to user-tier "Built-in", a
#[sub] distinct bucket from app-tier "Built-in" (m_category_order
#[sub] carries the is_app_tier discriminant). active_category just
#[sub] returns the name string; the tier discriminant isn't observable
#[sub] through this query alone, but the visual is "panel jumps to a
#[sub] Built-in category that's freshly user-tier."
assert pnl_styles active_category == "Built-in"
styles delete app_dup
#[sub] After delete, the user-tier "Built-in" category is empty (the
#[sub] only entry was the just-deleted duplicate). The panel's
#[sub] category-deleted recovery (build_chooser) falls through to
#[sub] index 0 of the rebuilt order — typically back to app-tier
#[sub] "Built-in". Visual `get` for diagnostic; no assert because
#[sub] the fallback target depends on the exact category list.
get pnl_styles active_category

#[sub] === Phase 3: TEAR DOWN ===
#[sub] Delete every test style we created. Each delete pushes a
#[sub] RemoveStyleCommand which snapshots the full Style for round-trip
#[sub] undo (unlike RemoveSwatchCommand which only carries the id).

styles delete a
styles delete b
styles delete c
styles delete a_dup

#[sub] Verify cleanup. count should be back to baseline. Visual
#[sub] inspection of the id lists below confirms no residue remains
#[sub] in either tier. If count differs from baseline, the test left
#[sub] residue in the project.

get styles count
assert styles count == count_before
get styles user_ids
get styles app_ids

#[sub] Registry sanity — list at end. `styles` should appear exactly
#[sub] once, alongside `layers` / `guides` / `swatches` and the other
#[sub] registered entries. No `styles.<id>` entries despite the many
#[sub] transient proxies materialised across this run (one per dotted
#[sub] addressing line above, every proxy destroyed at end-of-statement).

list

#[sub] s222 m1 smoke complete — collection verbs, proxy verbs, proxy
#[sub] queries, app-tier guard, find_by_name, the duplicate " copy"-
#[sub] naming, and category round-trips all exercised. Every mutating
#[sub] verb pushed a command into history; manual Ctrl+Z after this
#[sub] script finishes should walk the undo stack back through every
#[sub] operation.
